    "reasoning": "Now I have all the information I need to answer the question. Let me calculate the annualized Q1 2026 AI capex and compare it with the other figures.\n\nKey figures:\n- FY2025 Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA: $7,168 million\n- FY2025 consolidated capex: $20,737 million\n- Q1 2026 AI capex: $7,723 million\n- Q1 2026 AI capex annualized: $7,723 \u00d7 4 = $30,892 million\n\nLet me calculate the ratios:\n- Connectivity Adj EBITDA / FY2025 consolidated capex = $7,168 / $20,737 = 34.6%\n- Connectivity Adj EBITDA / Q1 2026 AI capex annualized = $7,168 / $30,892 = 23.2%\n\nLet me also calculate the segment-level Adjusted EBITDA:\n- Space: $653 million\n- Connectivity: $7,168 million\n- AI: $(1,237) million\n- Total: $6,584 million\n\nSo Connectivity represents $7,168M / $6,584M = 108.9% of total Adjusted EBITDA (because AI is negative).\n\nThe Connectivity segment is clearly the most capable internal cash source. Let me also calculate the Q1 2026 annualized AI capex more precisely.\n\nQ1 2026 AI capex annualized = $7,723M \u00d7 4 = $30,892M\n\nLet me also note that the Q1 2026 consolidated capex was $10,107M, so annualized that would be $40,428M.\n\nNow let me think about the risks if Connectivity's growth slows:\n1. ARPU decline - already declining from $99 to $66/month\n2. Competition from terrestrial and satellite providers\n3. Satellite replacement costs and depreciation\n4. International expansion costs\n5. Government revenue decline\n6. Supply chain concentration\n7. Regulatory and spectrum risks\n\nIf Connectivity's growth slows, the company would face:\n- Reduced internal cash generation to fund AI capex (which is annualizing at ~$31B)\n- Increased reliance on external financing (which was $7.1B in Q1 2026)\n- Potential need to slow AI investment\n- Risk of being unable to sustain the multi-year AI investment horizon\n\nLet me also calculate the gap between Connectivity Adj EBITDA and the AI capex annualized:\n$30,892M - $7,168M = $23,724M gap\n\nSo even if Connectivity's entire Adjusted EBITDA were redirected to AI capex, it would only cover about 23% of the annualized AI capex run-rate.\n\nLet me also calculate the consolidated capex annualized for Q1 2026:\n$10,107M \u00d7 4 = $40,428M\n\nAnd the consolidated Adjusted EBITDA was $6,584M for FY2025. So the gap between annualized Q1 2026 capex and FY2025 Adjusted EBITDA is:\n$40,428M - $6,584M = $33,844M\n\nThis is a massive gap that requires external financing.\n\nLet me now formulate the final answer.\n\nActually, let me also verify the calculations using the calculator tool.",
